1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Let's talk about one of my favorite subjects. Fire!

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:40,000
Let's talk about one of my favorite subjects. Fire!

3
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Now, it's good to think about fire from a physical security perspective as a risk.

4
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:50,000
And with any risk, the deal, the way that we want to deal with that risk is by putting in place

5
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:54,000
and mitigating controls, specifically a complete control.

6
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:59,000
And a complete control, of course, is a combination of preventive, detective, and corrective.

7
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:06,000
So, how do we prevent a fire? Well, the best way to prevent fire is to not have any combustible materials,

8
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:12,000
anything that will burn. And so, for example, in a data center, if you're bringing in new servers,

9
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:15,000
you want to make sure that you unpack the servers on the loading dock.

10
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:20,000
We've all a very combustible cardboard on the loading dock. And what are you bringing to the server room?

11
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Just the bare metal servers. So this is a perfect example of how we try and prevent fire.

12
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Don't have any combustible materials. Now, preventive, detective, and corrective.

13
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:36,000
If we do have a fire, the very first thing we want to be able to do is quickly as possible is detect the fire.

14
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:38,000
And that's what we're going to talk about in this module.

15
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:44,000
And then the final thing, if we have detective fire, is quickly as possible we want to try and correct a fire.

16
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:49,000
And in the next module, we'll talk about different types of fire, correction, or fire suppression systems.

17
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:56,000
So let's talk about methods we can use to detect a fire. There's three major methods that we can use.

18
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:04,000
We can use what are known as flame detectors. These are basically video cameras that look for infrared or UV light.

19
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:08,000
And so they can see the flames that are looking up from a fire.

20
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:13,000
But we want to try and detect a fire as early as possible. And if you're at the point where you've got big,

21
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:20,000
licking flames like behind me here, that's not a very good way to detect a fire as early as possible.

22
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:24,000
The next method that we can use are what are known as heat detectors.

23
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:28,000
And heat detectors are just like they sound like they're basically temperature sensors.

24
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:34,000
And they look for a rapid rise in temperature. And so you'd have these heat sensors spread around your facility.

25
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:40,000
And if one or two of them detect a rapid rise in temperature, that's a pretty good indication that you have a fire.

26
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:45,000
But again, if you're at the point where the temperature is spiking, the fire is pretty far along.

27
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:50,000
So heat detectors are not necessarily the best way to detect a fire as early as possible.

28
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:58,000
And that leads us to the last and probably most important method to detect a fire as early as possible. And that's smoke detectors.

29
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:01,000
And there's a number of different types of smoke detectors we're going to talk about here.

30
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:05,000
Let's start with what are known as ionization sensors.

31
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:13,000
Ionization sensors, the way they work, it's actually quite cool. They have a small amount of radioactive material inside the smoke detector.

32
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:18,000
And it actually ionizes particles. And these particles flow between two metal plates.

33
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:26,000
And what happens if smoke particles enter this little chamber, the smoke particles will actually disrupt the flow of ionized particles.

34
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:31,000
And therefore allow you to detect fire. So that's ionization sensors.

35
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:35,000
The next most common are what are known as photoelectric.

36
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:42,000
And again, this is kind of neat how this works. So in a photoelectric sensor, you have a light source and a sensor.

37
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:46,000
And the light source is pointed a little off angle. So it's not pointed right at the sensor.

38
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:55,000
And what happens is if smoke particles pass through the sensing chamber, the smoke particles will actually cause the light to reflect into the sensing area.

39
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:05,000
And so if the sensor suddenly picks up that light's being reflected into the sensor, that's an indication that smoke particles are passing through the sensor and you have a fire.

40
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:11,000
Now, most of the sensors that we use nowadays in homes and most common business ones are what are known as dual sensors.

41
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:17,000
And just as name implies, they're a combination of both ionization and photoelectric.

42
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:21,000
And there's one final type of smoke detection system that you should know about.

43
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:30,000
And this is the most sensitive type of system. And it's very aptly named. It's called the Vesda system, which stands for very early smoke detection apparatus.

44
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:36,000
So just as the name implies, these systems are really good at detecting a fire as early as possible.

45
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:42,000
But these systems are not commonly seen because they're very, very sensitive and they're very expensive.

46
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:47,000
So where you tend to see Vesda systems are in places like data centers and museums.

47
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:52,000
But if you ever get a question asking you, what is the best way to detect a fire as early as possible?

48
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:58,000
It's smoke detectors, look first for smoke detectors and the best type of smoke detector, Vesda.

